<section class="diagram-block">
  <div class="diagram-header">
    <p class="eyebrow">Segmentation diagram</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Trust boundaries by zone</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      The lab is intentionally separated into management, lab, attacker, victim, SOC, VPN, and quarantine-oriented zones instead of one flat network.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="seg-grid">
    <div class="seg-card management">
      <h3>Management</h3>
      <p>Proxmox management, administrative SSH, cluster UI.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card cluster">
      <h3>Cluster / Internal</h3>
      <p>Internal services and cluster communication.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card lab">
      <h3>Lab / Server Zone</h3>
      <p>Internal infrastructure and general lab workloads.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card attacker">
      <h3>Attacker Zone</h3>
      <p>Red-team style machines and noisy testing systems.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card victim">
      <h3>Victim Zone</h3>
      <p>Simulated endpoints, services, and demonstration targets.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card soc">
      <h3>SOC / Monitoring</h3>
      <p>Logging, monitoring, traffic analysis, and detection tooling.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card vpn">
      <h3>VPN Clients</h3>
      <p>Administrative peer address space for WireGuard access.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card aquarium">
      <h3>Aquarium / Quarantine</h3>
      <p>Malware detonation, packet capture, artifact collection, rollback-driven analysis.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="seg-card simulation">
      <h3>Controlled Internet Simulation</h3>
      <p>Fake services, sinkhole behavior, INetSim-style observation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

